<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-549-451  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 549 451.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Sept 24 1990 v7 n39 p35(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New transponders to ease int'l satellite link shortage. (NASAsatellite C-band transponders)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Molloy, Maureen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Twenty-four transponders on two National Aeronautics and SpaceAdministration (NASA) satellites will relieve the current capacityshortage in international satellite links when they becomecommercially available for use in early 1991.andP;  ColumbiaCommunications Corp will control the C-band transponders on twoNASA tracking and data relay satellite systems (TDRSS).andP;  TheC-band transponders are separate from the Ku-and S-bandtransponders used for space shuttle operations and communicationswith scientific satellites.andP;  Columbia does not plan to leasecapacity directly to end users, but making the transpondersavailable to carriers should help ease the shortage ofinternational satellite links.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Columbia Communications Corp. (Contracts).andO;Topic:     Satellite CommunicationsTranspondersInternational CommunicationsTelecommunicationsCommunications Service SuppliersUnited States. National Aeronautics and Space AdministrationGovernment Contracts.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>